						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Dwedit wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I thought BRK was more intended to be like RST on the Z80, a way of calling a preset address using a smaller instruction.</div>
<br />
<br />Every single 6502, 65c02, and 65816 book I have indicates BRK was solely designed for debugging use, and the signature byte (despite being ignored, e.g. PC+1) used for determining what BRK statement got executed where.
<br />
<br />The official MOS documentation seems to imply that the purpose of BRK was to handle unique cases of EPROM flashing (since apparently zeroes were hard to deal with on old EPROM flashers -- this is outside of my knowledge set).</div>

